    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_333896">Bought the 4th ed book because I am a Shadowrun fan from the first ed of the game. Been reading it off and on in my spare time, even if I never get to play or run another campaign due to my work schedule, and I have liked most of what I have seen in the game. I haven't gotten through the magic section yet but I will say this. Shadowrun always frontloaded magic types on character creation. You always bought as much foci as possible because it would be far cheaper to bond it at creation then at any other point. However, assuming they haven't changed linked magic foci, then the usual answer to an overfocied caster is to simply attack the focused item from astral space and destroy it. Assuming your the GM of course. <br />
<br />
Had a similar problem in 2nd ed with a wolf shaman with about 5 spell locks and a powerfocus 3. He was spelllocked with +4dice iniative, +4cha, int, will, and I think either body or a personal barrier spell. Could summon up nasty elementals, soak rediculous drain from spells or summoning, and moved faster then the street sam. <br />
<br />
An active foci (spell lock, summoning foci, etc) is visable in astral space, and spell locks where extremely easy to break. If the character is running around all the time with foci active he is just begging to have stuff shattered. Nevermind if some really POed mage chooses to channel a physical spell through a spell lock to have it manifest in the regular world from astral space. Shadowrun is a tough place and there there can be &quot;gangs&quot; in astral space which could consist of anything from groups of magicially aware punks to toxic spirits on a rip. Also, check the rules for barriers/wards. I think trying to pass through one with an active foci might result in a combat, with the ward winning in all probability.</div>
