    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_335371">Ok here is what I am seeing with spellcasting.<br />
<br />
1)Spells no longer have a learned max force rating, you just learn a spell and you can cast it upto your magic rating only taking stun drain. Anything over your magic rating (upto x2) is physical drain.<br />
<br />
2)Caster casts the spell with magic attribute + sorcery. Damage is force rating + success - resist rolls (which is either willpower or body +1/2 armor).<br />
<br />
3)Drain roll is willpower + (cha or logic) vs (spell force/2) + (a modifier based on the spell) in blocks of drain taken.<br />
<br />
The problem I am seeing here is that a caster with a high magic and sorcery rating can cast low force spells that aren't any easier to resist by the target, but whose drain is laughably easy to resist. Add in a good powerfocus and the mage is going to be nasty. And it would be relatively easy this mage to cast 2 or 3 spells at once, still taking no drain. <br />
<br />
Only quick fix I can see around this would be to increase the + modifier to make it less easy for the caster to get away with casting lots of low force combat spells without badly affecting casting higher force spells.  Even a +2 should change slinging low force spells quite a bit, every +1 needs 3 dice to effectively counteract the additional drain. <br />
<br />
BTW the rule for casting the increased reflexes spell are trash. The threshhold is one higher then the init boost (4 success for +3in and 3passes for example. The mage only needs to cast the spell at force 4 to be able to get maximum effect, and the drain tests is not major so that the mage can cast the spell over and over with little chance of taking drain until he gets 4 successes at which he uses the sustaining focus to keep the spell running. This is something all GMs should look at and modify. If they want the drain to remain low then the threshholds need to be  increased. <br />
<br />
So magicians &quot;hang&quot; a spell on a sustained foci instead of a spell lock. The idea is neat and I like it. But if a mage keeps spells continously active through one I would still think he would have a chance to attract unwanted astral attention. <br />
<br />
As for the 3 rated 6 wolf spirits, are those bound or unbound spirits? Because unless I am reading something wrong a mage may only have one unbound spirit at a time (page 179 4th full paragraph).  A mage summon a spirit and have it in standby but that costs a service.  A mage may have multiple bound spirits (equal to cha) but each one takes hours to summon and bind and is somewhat expensive. Summoning a spirit for Binding means an opposed roll of Magic + Binding against twice the spirit's force. The resist roll is twice the TOTAL success the spirit made in the opposed test. <br />
<br />
So if the magician is trying to summon a bound spirit force 6, it takes 6 hours, 3000yen, then he has to roll his magic + binding against 12 dice. Lets say the spirit gets 4 success. He then has to resist 8 blocks of damage. Against a force 6 spirit the mage isn't likely to get very many services either. And, even though it doesn't actually say it, its very likely that if the magician fails to get more success in the summoning attempt then the spirit rolls to resist then the spirit is summoned, POed, and the mage is still having to resist drain. After all, the roll is basically to see if the mage can command the spirit, not summon it up in the first place. <br />
<br />
Its always been best for magic characters to buy magic foci in character gen, and the tradition continues. Nothing that can be done about this. But after having spent 55 points to be a magician (15 for ability, 40 for magic attribute of 5) it would seem a magician would start rapidly running out of build points. If he bought a rank 3 power focus, rank 4 sustaining focus (minimum needed for +3initi) , and a rank 4 summoning wolf focus that is 175000yen, or 35 build points. Then he has to bind them (another 11 build). Now he needs spells. Say 10 spells = 30 build points. 131 points so far and not one skill point. Also, has no equipment. So while a magician can buy alot of foci right out of the box, its gonna cost them elsewhere.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
