    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_406685">3rd or 4th edition? I know a lot about SR but never have played 4th. Also depends on what type of character you want to play. Magic user, street samurai , rigger, adept, decker (if you GM allows it, a lot don't), etc.<br />
<br />
4th you have:<br />
<br />
<br />
Main book<br />
Street Magic: Magic Book<br />
Augmentation: Cyberware book that is soon to be released<br />
<br />
3rd you have:<br />
<br />
Main Book<br />
Shadowrun Companion: rules for the point system, as well as edges and flaws<br />
Magic in the Shadows : Magic Book<br />
Matrix: Decker and general matrix info<br />
Rigger 3: Vehicles and drones, rigger stuff mostly<br />
Man and Machine: Cyberware, bioware, nano-tech<br />
Cannon Companion: Book of guns, armor, and other toys. <img src="images/smilies/emote_smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smile" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
<br />
Websites:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://forums.dumpshock.com/" target="_blank">Dumpshock Forums</a> <br />
Great SR forum<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.shadowrun4.com/" target="_blank">Official Shadowrun Site</a><br />
<br />
Note: there is a game for the Xbox 360 and PC also titled Shadowrun. While a fun game, do not use it as a reference. They changed a LOT of stuff from the PnP game in the video game. (For example, there is no teleportation or resurrection magic in the PnP game, Dwarves don't drain essence, etc.)</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
